segments.text: chila coffee.

So we had corn plots tests growing at all these locations and we'd send them the seed to plant and then go around in the fall and take notes on the crop and evaluate the hybrids so that we had different hybrids for different environmental areas.
And the one thing that has always been a tremendous importance to me and a value
is the contacts I had with the superintendents at these different stations.
They were really a tremendous group of people, diverse as could be, but everyone was likable, and they were effective people and committed to their work, and they just loved what they were doing.
I've mentioned a few names.
There was Bill Friend at Wesley Cole.
I can't remember all the initials.
Hall at Beeville, Stansel at
Angleton, Henry Hill at Temple, Johnson at Tyler, Shorty Morris at Nacogdoches, Roy Quimby, who you've probably heard of, at Chillicothe, and a fellow named Don Jones out at Lubbock.
I think these people deserve, these leaders in the different areas deserve a tremendous amount of credit for what they've done.
efforts like the corn project, did they have plots at many of the stations using the new, hopefully the new varieties of corn?
That's correct, yes.
We would carry out what we'd call a breeding function.
We'd develop the lines and make the experimental crosses and then send a series of crosses to each of these locations.
And then they'd harvest the plots in the fall.
And we'd go around there and take notes on them, make observations, and make selections of the best hybrids.
So they played an integral role in, in this case, the development of hybrid corn.
But of course, they were carrying on other activities that related to their particular area.
For example, in the valley, they'd be working with vegetables and fruits a lot.
on this particular project.
When did y'all begin to think that you were making some progress?
How many years did it take?
Well, I'd say that Dr. Mangelsdorf started in the development in the early 30s.
And we were beginning to have the first few hybrids introduced in 41, 42, and just improved from then on.
We introduced, oh, I'd say half a dozen hybrids during the early war years, and I was gone during 45 and back in 46.
And we then had additional and improved, I'd say a second group of hybrids came along in the late 40s as a result of this joint program all around the state.
So it was a...
an interesting time in this particular project area.
What was your response as a typical Texas farmer to these new varieties?
They were generally eager to accept them, yes.
We were obtaining yield increases of I'd say 15 to 30 percent.
Of course, one of the reactions, they didn't like to pay the higher price for the seed.
which they'd been accustomed to harvesting their crop and just replanting, usually, and having a seed cost.
I've forgotten now what the cost is, but you end up costing a few dollars an acre for the hybrid seed.
In that era, Texas corn was usually fed to the animals locally?
A lot of it was, yes.
Just over a period of time,
changed somewhat from being used on the farm where it was grown to being collected in elevators and maybe fed locally by feeders locally.
And by now, I'd say some of it goes clear up to the feedlots.
And what also happened over a period of time, and this gets on up into the 50s and 60s, the corn acres declined dramatically
But the yield went up so that today we have, instead of five million acres, we have two million.
But the average yield is over 100 bushels an acre.
So we're actually, I figured this out, producing more corn probably than we did in 1940.
And you said 15 bushels maybe with the old corn?
The average yield per acre.
Yes, that's correct.

It's a little over 100, very little, 110 or so, but we'd be producing more now on the 2 million acres by quite a bit than we were on the 5 million in 1940, and that's just an indication of one improvement in agriculture and what's happened overall with the improvement in seeds, fertilizers, herbicides, insecticides and all that.
You're a full-time member of the Experiment Station staff, working full-time on the corn project.
Correct.
Up to the war.
Then you go away, active duty.
I was gone just during 1945.
Then you come back.
Take the story from there and go forward.
All right.
I came back, started back at the Experiment Station beginning in 1946.
And...
I went off to graduate school in summer of 46.

I wanted to get a Ph.D. degree if I wanted to stay in this type of work because, as you're familiar with, you're somewhat restricted in advancement without a Ph.D. degree in an institution like A&M or any of the other major institutions.
So I went to school again with Dr. Manglethorpe, who was at Harvard.
and finally finished.
I stayed up there about a year and a half taking courses and did some thesis work back here in Texas, 48 and 49, and finally obtained a Ph.D. degree in 1949 from Harvard.
You were probably a rarity at A&M then.
There probably weren't many Harvard students here.
I really don't know.
I never thought to explore that.
Did you retain during those graduate study days, did you retain your position?
Yes, I was on leave and was able to go through a general education board fellowship.
I don't know whether you've run across those anywhere else or not, but it's a tremendous program, the Rockefeller Foundation.
When you come back, how did your routine change?
Well, there's one story that I guess I would say is a highlight of my career, if you want to call it that, or corn improvement generally in relation to the production of hybrid corn.
In 1944, before I
went away into service shortly before.
I noticed a plant that was what we call male sterile.
The silks represent the female part and the tassels the male part.
And the tassel was sterile.
It had branches but didn't exude any anthrax or anything.
And I'd remembered talking to Dr. Mangerthorff about sterile tassels.
back some years before when he was still here.
And he had talked about the possibility of using such a corn to produce hybrid corn without detasseling.

Don't want to go into detail, but to produce hybrid corn, you have to detassel one parent and let the other one shed pollen to produce the hybrid, which is a timely and time-consuming and costly operation.
Anything to be done to alleviate that would be a big improvement.

Well, we found this one plant in the greenhouse and made some crosses with it and kind of lost track of it while I was in the service, but I returned and started back making continued crosses with it and the plants retained their sterility, which meant that it was
cytoplasmically or maternally inherited.
The male sterile character was transmitted by the seed parent each time and stayed sterile.
In 19, after I came back from service, I guess it was right before I went to graduate school, in making some crosses with this sterile corn, male sterile corn,
crossed with some different lines, different inbreds, and one of them showed up fertile, which meant that here was a line that was capable of restoring fertility to this sterile form.
This is a fantastic situation if it would really work out, and it did.
I don't know the time span exactly, but...

When I got back from Harvard, we pursued it pretty rapidly and built up the quantities of the sterile corn in appropriate lines so that it could be used as a seed parent for producing hybrids and you wouldn't have to detassel it.
It wouldn't shed any power.
But you had to use then the restore lines
and the pollinator so that you'd restore fertility for the next generation so the farmer wouldn't have a crop of cobs.
There was a kind of an interim solution to this, too, though.
For a while, some of the companies were producing, say, two-thirds of their crop on sterile and a third on the tasseled corn, which would be fertile, and then blending the two so that you'd
get enough pollen in the farmer's field to produce seed, produce grain.
But if you got the restorers in there, you didn't have to do any blending either.
And I don't remember.
This development really exploded once it got out into the industry because it was such a fantastic saving.
And along there in the late 40s, early 50s was
I don't know what the proportions were, but a tremendous amount of seed acreage planted through this sterile restore system.
It really had a dramatic effect on the industry.
In the success of this long program, are there any individuals that deserve special credit?
the people that gave Project Wheel support?
Any governors or members of the legislature, A&M administrators?
Well, of course, the Experiment Station administrators.
And Tom Harrington, I believe, was president or chancellor along in there.
And there's a write-up in one of the annual reports.
I don't remember why Tom was here.
There's another element of the story here.
But yes, I'd say there was support in the institution for it.
And yes, the Department of Agriculture was supporting part of the research.
And they were quite excited about the development, and particularly the director of the experimental state.
He was R.D.
Lewis.
Did you know him?
Yeah.
He was very supportive of it and was, of course, able to see that it went ahead.
Let me just finish this male sterile story while I'm on it.
It goes ahead time-wise.
So during the 50s, the industry just moved to this sterile restore system of production.
And you asked about the credit.
that somewhere in the 50s, I believe it was the mid-50s, a lawsuit instituted.
Have you ever heard any of this?
I didn't know that it was published at the university about it off and on in the past.
A lawsuit instituted by Research Corporation of America.
I believe that's the name of it.
I don't know the Research Corporation.
It's the Rockefeller.
subsidiary or something they'd founded.
And Mangelsdorf and Jones, I didn't tell you, Jones was a corn breeder in Connecticut at the Experiment Station in Connecticut.
He had worked with Mangelsdorf.
And they had talked about this procedure for some time.
So they...
started a lawsuit against the industry for using the system without paying royalties for it to them.
And this hassle went on for a period of several years.
And I gave, oh, what do you call it?
Give a legal report out of court.
I can't think of the name of it right now.
Deposition.
Deposition.
And then we were in court a time or two.
I think the case was tried in Chicago in the mid-60s.
Well, the upshot of it was that the Research Corporation won.
The industry was alive.
responsible for making the payment to him.
I was in some awkward condition, position, since I had done the developmental activity of it, actually.
And Jones, and the minor folks, to some extent, thought up the idea and all this and that.
So it was a question, I guess, of who deserved credit
Anyway, they won the lawsuit, and the industry had to pay royalty.
But they just had to pay them during the last years the patent was available, and they would almost run out by the time they finished the lawsuit.
So the industry paid some money.
I don't remember how much.
It was a significant amount.
It would have been in the millions of dollars, I'm sure.
But then in either 1970 or 1971,
We had a tremendous blight take over the corn crop in the United States, and it was a big national story.
I don't know whether you had to bed in a cave and run into it or not.
But the corn crop was reduced by a third or two thirds of a tremendous production due to the blight, and the blight was
related to this male sterile character.
The male stericorn blighted and the non-male stericorn didn't.
So all of a sudden, here was all this seed and inventory that was blight-susceptible, and of course nobody wanted to plant it.
So there was a rapid change in the industry from the sterile form back to the normal form where you do tassels.
And it was just all kind of hullabaloo in 71 about that.
And everybody's scrambling.
I was in the seed business then, scrambling around to get non-sterile corn.
And since then, it hadn't been used much.
There has been another form or two that are used to some extent, forms that are not susceptible to the blight.
But anyway, the story went on from the mid-40s to the 70s.
And did you stay with corn during all those years?
Yes, primarily.
Well, maybe I better go back to when I came back from my graduate work, finished in 1949, and then I went back, continued my job.
I was just on leave and continued working in charge of the corn improvement program.
But in 1956, I became head of the Department of Agronomy.
and didn't really have time to do any work anymore.
But I didn't last very long, only a couple years.
I came here in 56 and resigned in 58.
Describe the Department of Agronomy at that time in terms of its number of faculty and who were its key people and so forth.
All right.
Let me back up just a little.
I think I mentioned earlier that the Experiment Station and the Agricultural Extension Service were separate from the College of Agriculture.
And in 1946, at the recommendation of the committee that had studied the subject, they combined those three agencies under a chancellor of agriculture, I believe.

It affected the department tremendously because there was a teaching department of agronomy, a research department of agronomy, and there wasn't literally an extension department of agronomy, but there were agronomists in the extension service.
So these three branches were all put together in one department as part of the agricultural system.
That happened in 46, 47.
So when I became department head in 40, excuse me, 56, a man by the name of Dr. Adams had been department head from 46 to 56, implementing this coordinated department effort.
And that was pretty well established at the time.
I became head in 56.
I'm going to guess we had 30 or 40 staff members in agronomy locally here.
Who were the most nationally known members?
In the department?
Okay.
I'm more familiar with the people in the plant science area than I am in soil science.
Agronomy covers both.
and subjects.
T.R.
Richmond was the cotton leader, and he was well-known nationally.
I.M.
Atkins was the small grain leader, and both of them were well-known nationally and internationally.
Now, some of the agronomists that
weren't literally in the department here, but they were located at these substations I mentioned, and they could be considered, I guess, agronomists.
They were part of the system anyway.
Hank Beechel, whom you may have heard of as a rice breeder at Beaumont, and he became world, he's a Borlaug type now.
World-renowned rice breeder, and spent some years in the Philippines,
He did some part of the Green Revolution work.
He's 93 years old now, I think, and still gets out in the fields and lives down here at Alvin, I believe.
Atkins, as you say, was the wheat breeder.
But J.R. Quindy, who you've heard of, I think, he's gotten several awards around the state.
The nation was internationally known as the Sardine Authority.
A man named Kenny Porter was also in small grains.
He was located out of Amarillo at the experiment station there.
And in the soils program, probably J.D.
Page was widely known.
Do you know him?
He was a soil physicist.
Adams himself was head during the 50s.
There was well-known soil fertility work.
A couple of fellows, Fisher and Caldwell in soil chemistry.
Frank Fudge was a soil chemist who had been stationed for a number of years in the department.
During that era, was almost all of the research funding from appropriated state and federal money?
Was there much private money supporting research?
No, there was not much private money.
And I don't know just what the balance would be between state and federal, but there was a lot of federal money in supporting programs.
The Bankhead Jones Act provided funds.
I've forgotten the name of the other one.
And annually, we'd have inspectors come down from the US Department of Agriculture and review the projects and make recommendations.
But there was very little private money.
In the corn project, we did have some industry funding.
The industry itself provided.
certain funding on a percentage basis on sales and marketing of hybrid corn.
It was, oh, at that time, substantial.
About $50,000, $100,000 annually.
When you became department head, who was the dean?
Whom did you report as department head?
That was the first thing President Rutter asked me when I resigned, who I reported to, and I never was quite sure.
The administration of the land-grant system is complex and even questionable, I could say.
Anyway, the department heads had three bosses, the director of extension,
Director of the Experiment Station, and the Dean of the College of Agriculture.
John Hutchinson was Director of the Extension Service.
Artie Lewis was Director of the Experiment Station.
No, not just yet.
I'm trying to sort out the dean situation.
Dean Shepardson was dean of agriculture, the teaching part during the 50s, and he was appointed to the Federal Reserve Board, I believe, and left.
Dr. Adams, who was head of agronomy,
became dean of agriculture, and he didn't stay but a year or two, and his fruit basket turned over there for a few years.
He went off to Nevada, and I believe Jack Miller became dean after that, and he'd already gotten there because he left for Oregon.
I didn't mean that as a total answer.
Well, John Hutcherson, well, I shouldn't say he was one of the good old boys, exactly, but you just dealt with him like you would the fellow next door or anything.
He encouraged you and supported you.
I'd say took a positive outlook on the projects, activities, and tried to lead by example.
Of course, I knew him personally pretty well.
But I think he followed that general procedure with the individuals who reported to him.
And I would judge he's a very successful administrator.
He stayed in that job.
for 20 years.
Dr. Lewis was not so much that way.
He was demanding in some ways.
But he would recognize merit in activities and was
I'd certainly say personally, very supportive.
We just went about it in a different way, though.
At least that's my recollection.
And for you as department head, is it difficult to report to three different places?
Well, administratively, it's somewhat confusing, yes.
Oh, I was going to tell you about President Ruggs.
I was just in this job two years.
And I think Jack Miller was the dean I remember.
He left about the same time I did.
But we had a vice chancellor of agriculture also in the picture.
And that was D.W. Williams at that time.
And he was the one who called me up and offered me the job.
not these other people.
So you just missed an echelon there.
So when I resigned, I wrote him a letter.
He hired me.
I'm sure I sent copies to the deans and directors.
But I got a phone call the next day from Rudder and said, I want you to come over to my office.
I don't think I'd met him.
He had
just started, I believe, maybe just a few months, as a president, a few months before, said, what did you write the chancellor for to resign?
Why didn't you write to the dean?
You report to the dean.
Well, Mr. President, whatever I called him, he was the fellow who hired me, and so I thought it was appropriate to send him a letter about my employment or anything to resign.
And I bet he talked to me 10 or 15 minutes or maybe 30, a good while for a president to spend time with, I thought.

And I think it had some effect on some of his thinking later, maybe, because they did some things, I think, to kind of straighten the administration out so that at least they all were on the same page.
I surely got the impression he felt like the dean was the one that he should report to.
No, I resigned.
I went in the industry.
Right.
As you look back on your career at A&M and your students there this year,
What did being an Aggie mean?
What did it mean to you in your life when you came up here and studied and so forth?
Well, there is to me, I think I've
talked earlier about the core involvement and not to the extent that I think it had an effect on me, but I value greatly the core experience, even though it was just for the two years.
Living under those conditions and the associations you develop.
